            "name": "backstory",
            "value": "Simone Miller\u2019s story is woven into the very fabric of San Francisco. Born and raised in the Fillmore District, she remembers a neighborhood humming with a different rhythm than it does today. Her father was a Muni driver for 30 years, his route a map of the city\u2019s working class, while her mother worked as a dedicated home health aide. They didn\u2019t have much, but their life was rich with community. That foundation was shaken when Simone was 15; her father suffered a debilitating back injury, forcing him onto disability. For the first time, the Millers had to navigate the complex, often intimidating world of public assistance. Simone never forgot the kindness of the eligibility worker who treated her parents with respect, not pity.\n\nThat experience became her North Star. Foregoing college, which felt like an unattainable luxury, Simone took a clerical exam for the City and landed an entry-level position right out of high school. She was diligent and sharp, learning the labyrinthine rules of social programs from the inside out. Over the years, she passed promotion exams, steadily climbing the ladder until she earned her current role as an Eligibility Worker at the Human Services Agency\u2014the very job held by the woman who had once helped her family.\n\nNow 37, Simone lives in a rent-controlled apartment in the Inner Richmond, a world away from the Fillmore of her youth. Her daily routine is a ritual of city life: the crisp morning walk to the 5-Fulton bus, the heavy caseloads where she sees her family\u2019s past reflected in the faces across her desk, and the decompressing ride home with her headphones on. She\u2019s single, having ended a long-term relationship a few years ago, and finds fulfillment in her tight-knit circle of friends, Sunday dinners with her mother, and spoiling her goddaughter.\n\nSimone\u2019s connection to San Francisco is one of fierce, protective love. She sees both the beauty and the brutal inequity of the city she serves. Her dream isn\u2019t grand; it\u2019s grounded. She hopes to one day secure a supervisor position to mentor new workers. And privately, she saves relentlessly, nurturing the quiet, almost impossible hope of buying a small condo\u2014a permanent stake in the city that has been her entire world."
        },
