            "@type": "PropertyValue",
            "name": "reveries",
            "value": "1.\nShe remembers being seven, the rumble of her father's 22-Fillmore bus a familiar song. He\u2019d let her sit on the worn vinyl seat right behind him, and through the giant front window, the city was a kingdom he commanded. He\u2019d catch her eye in his large rearview mirror and wink, a secret pact between them. That was before his injury, when her love for San Francisco was simple and pure, cemented by the proud, steady hands of her father steering them all home.\n\n2.\nAt 15, the shame in the Human Services Agency waiting room was a physical weight. Her father, a man of immense pride, stared at the floor, broken. But the eligibility worker spoke to him, not down to him. She saw a person, not a problem. In that small act of offering dignity, a fire was lit in Simone. She felt the heavy cloak of pity lift from her family\u2019s shoulders. That quiet moment of respect in a sterile office became the blueprint for her entire life.\n\n3.\nThe day she received her first city employee ID badge at 18 was monumental. The photo was terrible, but the laminated card felt like a shield. It wasn't a university acceptance letter, but for her, it was more significant. It was proof that she could carve out a place for herself, a tangible piece of the city that had nearly broken her family. Holding it, she felt not like a recipient of aid, but a part of the engine that made things run.\n\n4.\nAfter her big breakup at 34, she walked for hours, ending up at Ocean Beach as the fog rolled in. The cold spray felt like it was scouring her clean. Watching the waves crash relentlessly against the shore, she felt a profound sense of solitude, but not loneliness. The city itself, in its moody, magnificent gray, felt like a constant companion. It was a stark, resilient love that would remain, a foundation that couldn\u2019t be packed into a moving box and taken away from her.\n\n5.\nJust last month, a teenager sat stiffly beside her mother at Simone\u2019s desk\u2014shoulders hunched, eyes downcast with the same familiar mix of fear and defiance Simone once felt. Simone paused, pushed the application aside, and leaned forward. \"I know this is a lot,\" she said softly, looking right at the girl. \"I\u2019ve been there.\" In the flicker of understanding in the girl\u2019s eyes, Simone felt the immense, cyclical weight and purpose of her work. She wasn\u2019t just pushing paper; she was closing a circle."
